1
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:17,200
(MACHINE CLICKING)

2
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:21,600
Oh, typical bloke.
Straight to fixing his motor.

3
00:00:21,680 --> 00:00:24,520
That's the thing, Amy.
I am not a typical bloke.

4
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:27,400
Sorry, did I do something wrong? 'Cause
I'm getting kind of mixed signals here.

5
00:00:27,480 --> 00:00:29,240
Mixed signals? How?

6
00:00:29,320 --> 00:00:32,120
Oh, come on.
You turn up in the middle of the night,

7
00:00:32,200 --> 00:00:33,640
you get me out of my bed in my nightie,

8
00:00:33,720 --> 00:00:36,640
which you then don't let me change
out of for ages,

9
00:00:36,720 --> 00:00:38,520
and take me for a spin
in your time machine.

10
00:00:38,600 --> 00:00:41,840
No, no, you're right. No mixed signals
there. That is just a signal.

11
00:00:41,920 --> 00:00:43,920
Like a great big bat signal in the sky.

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,280
Get your coat, love. The Doctor is in.

13
00:00:46,360 --> 00:00:48,680
Yeah. No, no, no, no. It's...

14
00:00:49,160 --> 00:00:51,040
Not like that.
That's not what I'm like.

15
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:52,600
-Then what are you like?
-I don't know.

16
00:00:52,760 --> 00:00:54,000
Gandalf.

17
00:00:54,280 --> 00:00:56,080
Like a space Gandalf.

18
00:00:56,840 --> 00:00:59,720
Like the little green one
in Star Wars...

19
00:00:59,800 --> 00:01:02,720
You really are not. You are a bloke.

20
00:01:03,160 --> 00:01:04,240
I'm the Doctor.

21
00:01:04,320 --> 00:01:06,280
Every room you walk into,
you laugh at all the men

22
00:01:06,360 --> 00:01:07,680
and show off to all the girls.

23
00:01:07,760 --> 00:01:09,840
-Do not.
-What about Rory?

24
00:01:13,120 --> 00:01:14,160
You laughed!

25
00:01:14,240 --> 00:01:16,520
No! That was just an involuntary snort,

26
00:01:16,600 --> 00:01:18,720
of fondness.

27
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:20,760
You are a bloke and you don't know it.

28
00:01:20,840 --> 00:01:22,520
And here I am to help.

29
00:01:22,600 --> 00:01:23,600
That is not why you're here.

30
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:25,960
-Then why am I here?
-Because...

31
00:01:27,160 --> 00:01:29,520
Because I can't see it any more.

32
00:01:31,840 --> 00:01:33,120
See what?

33
00:01:33,280 --> 00:01:34,520
I'm 907.

34
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:37,800
After a while, you just can't see it.

35
00:01:37,880 --> 00:01:39,800
-See what?
-Everything. I look at a star

36
00:01:39,880 --> 00:01:41,440
and it's just a big ball of burning gas.

37
00:01:41,520 --> 00:01:43,600
And I know how it began
and I know how it ends,

38
00:01:43,680 --> 00:01:45,800
and I was probably there both times.

39
00:01:45,880 --> 00:01:48,760
Now, after a while,
everything is just stuff.

40
00:01:49,320 --> 00:01:51,560
That's the problem. You make
all of space and time your backyard

41
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:54,600
and what do you have? A backyard.

42
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:57,360
But you, you can see it.

43
00:01:57,440 --> 00:01:59,720
And when you see it, I see it.

44
00:01:59,880 --> 00:02:03,000
And that's the only reason
you took me with you?

45
00:02:03,120 --> 00:02:06,840
-There are worse reasons.
-(SNORTING) I was certainly hoping so.

46
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:10,960
Does that mean I'm not the first, then?

47
00:02:11,040 --> 00:02:13,880
There have been others
travelling with you.

48
00:02:14,520 --> 00:02:15,880
Yeah, sure.

49
00:02:16,200 --> 00:02:18,280
Loads of them.
But just friends, you know, chums,

50
00:02:18,360 --> 00:02:20,640
pals, mates, buddies.
Not mates, forget mates.

51
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:22,320
And out of all those friends,
how many would you say,

52
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:25,800
just out of curiosity, were girls?

53
00:02:26,320 --> 00:02:27,320
Oh.

54
00:02:29,120 --> 00:02:30,680
Some of them, I suppose.

55
00:02:30,760 --> 00:02:32,600
-Must have been.
-Some?

56
00:02:33,720 --> 00:02:35,360
It's hard to tell. It's a grey area.

57
00:02:35,440 --> 00:02:37,320
Under half? Over half?

58
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:39,760
Probably...slightly...

59
00:02:41,240 --> 00:02:42,440
a little bit over?

60
00:02:42,520 --> 00:02:43,720
Hmm. Young?

61
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:45,680
Everyone's young compared to me.

62
00:02:45,760 --> 00:02:47,200
(LAUGHS SARCASTICALLY) Hot?

63
00:02:47,280 --> 00:02:48,680
No. No, no, no, no.

64
00:02:48,760 --> 00:02:52,000
None of them. Not really. Not at all.
Probably not.

65
00:02:53,800 --> 00:02:55,880
Maybe one or two.
I didn't really notice.

66
00:02:55,960 --> 00:02:59,680
Well, this big old machine
must have some kind of visual records.

67
00:02:59,760 --> 00:03:01,920
Oh, God. I mean no, and anyway,
they're voice-locked.

68
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:03,240
Oh, voice-locked.

69
00:03:03,320 --> 00:03:04,880
So I would just have to say...

70
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:07,640
"Show me all visual records
of previous Tardis inhabitants.”

71
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:10,040
No. No, no, no. I mean voice-locked.

72
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:13,400
I would have to say, "Show me all visual
records of previous Tardis inhabitants.”

73
00:03:13,480 --> 00:03:14,560
Oh, thank you.

74
00:03:14,640 --> 00:03:17,400
-(BEEPING)
-No! No, no, no! No!

75
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:21,720
(AMY LAUGHING)

76
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:23,920
Oh, Gandalf.

77
00:03:24,280 --> 00:03:26,080
Thanks. Thanks, dear.

78
00:03:26,160 --> 00:03:28,560
Miss out the metal dog, why don't you?

79
00:03:28,640 --> 00:03:30,600
Is that a leather bikini?

80
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:33,560
Right. That's it. Rory.

81
00:03:33,640 --> 00:03:36,400
We're going to find Rory
and we're going to find him now.

82
00:03:36,480 --> 00:03:38,320
He's at a stag night.

83
00:03:38,480 --> 00:03:41,120
Well, then. Let's make it a great one.

